commits.message:
Merge pull request #1 from jlim128/DC-Dash

Dc dash app added

Create FullBodyDetectorv3.py

Code is used to detect a human's upper, lower and full body, using Computer Vision. Haar Cascades were used to detect the human. In order to find the direction of movement, an Optical Flow was mapped onto the grayscale image of the detected human. Doing vector math and finding averages of multi-dimensional matrices, we arrive at a value of the general velocity of the moving object. This moving value is used to determine direction, positive being towards the camera and vice versa. There is a 1.5 unit buffer extending from -0.75 to 0.75 to account for the low resolution camera used at the time of creation. Higher Resolution cameras and cameras that are capable of recording more frames  per second will require a lower buffer so that they don't miss a target. The population count is pushed to a database that uses a mongodb framework, which is planned to be used to be the backend of a webapp and an android app. The Code from v1-v3 was written in VS Code in Python 3.7.3 64-Bit, while the android app is being made on Android Studio

Create FullBodyDetectorv2.py

Code is an update to v1. v2 uses the concepts of Optical Flow to determine the direction in which the detected human object is going.

Create haarcascades_fullbody.xml

Haar Cascade XML file to detect full, lower and upper parts of a human body.  Also available on OpenCV's GitHub

Create FullBodyDetectorv1.py

Code uses functions of Computer Vision to precisely detect a human by scanning for upper, lower and full bodies. Code is written in Python using the "OpenCV" package and scans for humans using Haar Cascades. v1 does not yet have direction sensing implemented

Update and rename FullBodyDetector.py to FullBodyDetectorv1.py

Code doesn't account for direction of movement

Create FullBodyDetector.py

Code utilized capabilities of Computer Vision to precisely detect full, upper and lower body of a human, using Haar Cascades. Written in Python using the "OpenCV" library.
